00:02:41.640 --> 00:02:45.112
I used this expression
for the matrix element

00:02:45.112 --> 00:02:48.090
in terms of the
oscillator strengths

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:54.777
to give you a nice relationship
for strong transition

00:02:54.777 --> 00:02:58.530
as in the alkaline E lines,
where the oscillator strength

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:00.010
is close to 1.

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:04.240
You see that the
matrix element is

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:07.390
1 over square of 2
times the geometric mean

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:09.840
of the complete wave
lengths of the electron,

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:12.626
and the wave lengths
of the transition.

00:03:12.626 --> 00:03:16.500
So that's actually important
for the dipole approximation,

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:19.580
because the concurrent wave
lengths of the electron

00:03:19.580 --> 00:03:21.730
is very, very small.

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:23.850
So therefore if
the matrix element

00:03:23.850 --> 00:03:26.650
is the geometric
mean of the two,

00:03:26.650 --> 00:03:28.990
that means that
the matrix element

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:32.460
is smaller than the
optical wave lengths.

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:35.920
And therefore,
the matrix element

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:38.356
is the length scale,
the relevant length

00:03:38.356 --> 00:03:39.730
scale of the atom
for transition.

00:03:39.730 --> 00:03:42.570
It is smaller than the
optical wave lengths.

00:03:42.570 --> 00:03:46.640
And that means-- and we'll
talk about it today--

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:52.488
that in the expression E to
the IKR, KR is really small.

00:03:52.488 --> 00:03:54.364
So we can do the
dipole approximation.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:03:59.340
Now I have a question for you.

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:01.510
I did it, frankly,
