00:04:10.405 --> 00:04:11.300
strengths.

00:04:11.300 --> 00:04:14.030
And the sum rule limits it to 1.

00:04:14.030 --> 00:04:17.450
And if there's a really
strong transition,

00:04:17.450 --> 00:04:19.410
it kind of exhausts
the sum rule,

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:21.769
and this is what I
was talking about.

00:04:21.769 --> 00:04:27.400
But because the thought crossed
my mind after last lecture,

00:04:27.400 --> 00:04:32.360
if I don't add
something to it, you

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:36.950
may actually use it as a
proof, which would be wrong.

00:04:36.950 --> 00:04:41.430
That the matrix element cannot
be larger than what you see

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:43.430
on the right hand side.

00:04:43.430 --> 00:04:49.612
On the other hand, we discussed
in the context of Rydberg atoms

00:04:49.612 --> 00:04:53.554
that Rydberg atoms can
have huge matrix elements.

00:04:53.554 --> 00:05:04.735
Matrix elements
which [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:04.735 --> 00:05:07.650
but they can really become huge.

00:05:07.650 --> 00:05:12.676
So how do you reconcile
the fact that Rydberg atoms

00:05:12.676 --> 00:05:16.003
in large instates, in
states with large strengths

00:05:16.003 --> 00:05:20.670
of [INAUDIBLE] numbers can
have huge matrix elements.

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:22.960
How do you reconcile
it with our discussion

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:25.385
of oscillator strengths
and sum rules?

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:36.659
The answer is simple but subtle.

00:05:41.450 --> 00:05:45.980
So is it a proof that the
matrix elements are impossible?

00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:48.420
Or if big matrix elements,
huge matrix elements,

00:05:48.420 --> 00:06:01.020
are possible, what property
of the oscillator strengths

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:03.012
did I not emphasize?

00:06:25.422 --> 00:06:27.470
I mean, keep watching.

00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:32.120
So first, are there atoms which
have huge matrix elements?

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:32.850
Yes.

00:06:32.850 --> 00:06:33.726
Rydberg atoms.

00:06:33.726 --> 00:06:36.510
So the left hand side
can be really huge.

00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:38.750
On the right hand side,
we have the wave lengths

00:06:38.750 --> 00:06:45.100
of the transition
which can get large.

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:46.730
You have to count
the wave lengths.

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:49.650
But then you have the
oscillator strengths.

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:54.540
And the oscillator
strengths, the sum

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:57.440
of all oscillator
strengths is 1.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:00.810
But you have to be careful
that not all oscillator

00:07:00.810 --> 00:07:02.210
strengths have to be possible.

00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:23.660
The definition of the
oscillator strengths

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:27.320
involves frequency from
one state to the next.

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:30.220
And depending whether
you go up or down,

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:33.390
the frequency has
positive or negative side.

00:07:33.390 --> 00:07:35.520
So therefore we have a sum rule.

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:38.490
For the ground state,
all frequencies

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:40.940
are positive because
you can only go up.

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:43.145
So therefore the
sum rule is only

00:07:43.145 --> 00:07:44.980
very useful for
the ground state,

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:47.550
because all oscillator
strengths are positive.

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:50.635
And if one oscillator
strength is 1,

00:07:50.635 --> 00:07:55.080
you know no other transition
has any strength at all.

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:57.020
However when you
have an excited state

00:07:57.020 --> 00:07:59.900
and you find an oscillator
strength which is 1,

00:07:59.900 --> 00:08:02.683
you could still have a lot
of other strong transitions,

00:08:02.683 --> 00:08:05.016
but their oscillator strengths
are positive and negative

00:08:05.016 --> 00:08:09.580
and they compensate for
each other in the sum rule.

00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:11.600
So just be careful about that.

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:14.575
For the ground state-- and
this is what I've proven to you

00:08:14.575 --> 00:08:16.820
here, I think
fairly rigorously--

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:22.260
if you are in the ground state,
the transition matrix element

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:24.560
cannot be larger than
the geometric mean

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:28.642
of the [INAUDIBLE] wave lengths
and the [INAUDIBLE] wave

00:08:28.642 --> 00:08:29.160
lengths.

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:31.190
But for excited states,
you have to be careful,

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:33.389
because the oscillator
strengths can have cosines.

00:08:36.284 --> 00:08:36.784
OK.

00:08:40.768 --> 00:08:41.809
Any questions about that?

00:08:45.690 --> 00:09:11.010
Then let's talk quickly
about the third point

00:09:11.010 --> 00:09:13.910
I wanted to discuss.

00:09:13.910 --> 00:09:17.895
And this is the relationship
to the index of refraction.

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:27.712
The polarizability here is
responsible for the index

00:09:27.712 --> 00:09:28.656
of refraction.

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:36.260
Well, the polarizability
determines [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:39.830
evaluate the constant and use
whatever relation you want,

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:41.990
but for a common
physics purpose,

00:09:41.990 --> 00:09:43.880
this is sort of the
useful relation.

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:45.950
This is the index of refraction.

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:47.980
It's related to
the polarizability.

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:51.014
And assuming that the
polarizability is small,

00:09:51.014 --> 00:09:53.300
you get this, the
parallel extension.

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:56.430
So roughly saying n minus 1.

00:09:56.430 --> 00:09:59.290
The difference of the index
of refraction from the vacuum

00:09:59.290 --> 00:10:01.400
is proportionate to
the atomic density

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:04.570
times the polarizability.

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:05.100
OK.

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.815
And we know this is what we
derive from the perturbation

00:10:07.815 --> 00:10:09.440
theory, that the
polarizability depends

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:13.640
on a matrix element squared
and 1 over the cube.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:17.643
Now I want to sort of show you
that by just using that concept

00:10:17.643 --> 00:10:22.250
and putting in
phenomenologically dissipation,

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:26.040
we can get a full expression
what happens to a laser

00:10:26.040 --> 00:10:30.400
beam crossing an atomic medium,
like a [INAUDIBLE] condensate.

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.180
How much of the laser
beam is absorbed?

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:34.326
And what is the feature
of the laser beam.

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:46.975
In order to get interesting
or simple formula,

00:10:46.975 --> 00:10:50.430
I want to now parametrize
the matrix element

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:52.220
by this correlated gamma.

00:10:52.220 --> 00:10:54.870
This will turn out with
an actual [INAUDIBLE],

00:10:54.870 --> 00:10:56.995
but right now, since
we haven't talked

00:10:56.995 --> 00:10:59.140
about spontaneous
emission, just say

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:02.590
I replace the matrix
element by gamma.

00:11:02.590 --> 00:11:04.805
And then I can write
the index of refraction

00:11:04.805 --> 00:11:05.680
in the following way.

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:11.210
But the matrix element squared
is now parametrized by gamma.

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:14.130
I have also introduced
the coordinate sigma

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:17.790
0, which will later be
the lesson in absorption

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:18.920
for section for atoms.

00:11:18.920 --> 00:11:22.160
But again here, just use
it as a parametrization.

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:24.035
I mean, I've not introduced
any new concepts.

00:11:24.035 --> 00:11:29.260
I've just rewritten this
expression in this way,

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:35.340
involved sigma 0, which is a
cross-section, and gamma, which

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:36.814
is an actual light.

00:11:39.521 --> 00:11:40.020
OK.

00:11:56.180 --> 00:11:59.970
The polarizability depended--
that was perturbation

00:11:59.970 --> 00:12:03.615
theory-- 1 over the
energy denominator,

00:12:03.615 --> 00:12:07.340
or 1 over the [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:07.340 --> 00:12:13.390
Now we have used, with
the oscillator strengths,

00:12:13.390 --> 00:12:16.664
the analogy to a classical
harmonic oscillator.

00:12:16.664 --> 00:12:21.060
And at some level, you know
that every harmonic oscillator

00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:23.880
must have little bit of damping.

00:12:23.880 --> 00:12:28.210
And so the same applies
to atomic oscillators.

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:30.620
And if you can account
for the damping

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:35.140
by putting into the frequency
denominator of the [INAUDIBLE],

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:36.550
1 over delta.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:39.626
Give it an imaginary part.

00:12:39.626 --> 00:12:42.440
So I'm just telling
you here, yes.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:44.080
Every oscillator
has some damping,

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:47.420
and I can phenomenologically
accounting for the damping

00:12:47.420 --> 00:12:50.970
by making the resonant
frequency, or the tuning,

00:12:50.970 --> 00:12:54.020
slightly complex by
adding imaginary part.

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:12.370
Later on I want to express
all the tunings normalized

00:13:12.370 --> 00:13:16.730
to this line which is parallel
to a normalized [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:16.730 --> 00:13:19.550
imaginary part.

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:20.050
OK.

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:24.050
So we have the situation
that this expression, gamma

00:13:24.050 --> 00:13:28.540
over delta-- this
was the expression

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:31.650
for the polarizability--
now acquires

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:37.310
a small imaginary part, and that
means it's a complex number.

00:13:37.310 --> 00:13:40.730
And I can now take this
expression separate it

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:46.190
into an imaginary
part and a real part.

00:13:46.190 --> 00:13:47.960
So why do I do that?

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:51.355
Well, the index of
refraction appears

00:13:51.355 --> 00:13:53.650
in the propagation
of the plane wave.

00:13:53.650 --> 00:13:56.480
If you're a plane
wave, the key vector

00:13:56.480 --> 00:13:58.690
is no longer the key
vector in vacuum.

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:00.700
It's multiplied with
the index of refraction,

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:02.850
and that's what I do here.

00:14:02.850 --> 00:14:04.930
And now you see
that immediately,

00:14:04.930 --> 00:14:09.640
an imaginary part of
the index of refraction

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:10.830
leads to absorption.

00:14:17.285 --> 00:14:19.185
And the real part
leads to [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:23.940 --> 00:14:24.450
OK.

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:28.790
So what we have now is we have
this expression for the plane

00:14:28.790 --> 00:14:31.550
wave after it is propagated
through the medium.

00:14:31.550 --> 00:14:34.810
And we see there is
exponential absorption.

00:14:34.810 --> 00:14:36.410
Exponential absorption.

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:38.840
On resonance, we have
an optimal density

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:41.520
which is given by
this expression.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:46.710
And the second term here
give us a phase shift.

00:14:46.710 --> 00:14:49.210
And it's clear since we
have one medium which

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:54.485
has a certain thickness that the
optical density and the phase

00:14:54.485 --> 00:14:57.630
shift are related.

00:14:57.630 --> 00:14:58.270
Yes.

00:14:58.270 --> 00:15:01.040
If you're on resonance, you
have the maximum optical density

00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:03.250
and the maximum absorption.

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:05.030
And the optical
density, of course,

00:15:05.030 --> 00:15:07.450
is 1 over the
[INAUDIBLE] squared.

00:15:07.450 --> 00:15:08.420
[INAUDIBLE]

00:15:08.420 --> 00:15:12.950
Whereas for large detuning,
the phase shift goes as 1

00:15:12.950 --> 00:15:13.850
over delta.

00:15:13.850 --> 00:15:18.710
It's the dispersive
scaling with the tuning,

00:15:18.710 --> 00:15:22.580
and this is also what we
had when we started out.

00:15:22.580 --> 00:15:26.150
When we would have started out
with the polarizability and not

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:29.336
a decaying dissipation, because
far away from resonance,

00:15:29.336 --> 00:15:32.646
you simply have a regional
of dispersive effect,

00:15:32.646 --> 00:15:36.510
and dissipation doesn't occur.

00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:43.560
So anyway, I
thought I would just

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:47.110
show that to you because this
is a full understanding of what

00:15:47.110 --> 00:15:50.141
happens to optical views
when they pass the atomic

00:15:50.141 --> 00:15:50.640
[INAUDIBLE].

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:54.280
It's nothing else than
the polarizability

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:56.200
or the harmonic
oscillator response

00:15:56.200 --> 00:16:00.480
of an atom to
electromagnetic radiation.

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:05.000
The only thing which is
non-derivative here is--

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.750
and that's what we will
discuss later in this course--

00:16:07.750 --> 00:16:12.990
is in order to get the
final result, which

00:16:12.990 --> 00:16:15.290
you may want to use in
analyzing your data,

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:18.680
you have to set the
dissipative, the damping

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:21.410
of the harmonic oscillator,
equal with this gamma

00:16:21.410 --> 00:16:21.910
parameter.

00:16:21.910 --> 00:16:24.600
And that's something I cannot
tell you without talking about

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:27.530
spontaneous emission.

00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:30.575
So just to remind you, I
introduce big gamma just

00:16:30.575 --> 00:16:33.710
as a parametrization
of the matrix element.

00:16:33.710 --> 00:16:36.890
Then I introduce
phenomenologically little gamma

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:39.330
as just the damping of
the harmonic oscillator

00:16:39.330 --> 00:16:42.030
of those two quantities
for two levels [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:42.030 --> 00:16:43.016
are identical.

00:16:43.016 --> 00:16:45.650
And that's something I
cannot show you here,

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:48.876
because this requires discussion
of spontaneous emission

00:16:48.876 --> 00:16:51.330
and the other modes of
the electromagnetic field.

00:16:51.330 --> 00:16:54.047
This is not covered by
a discussion of the ac

00:16:54.047 --> 00:16:54.672
polarizability.

00:16:59.112 --> 00:16:59.612
OK.

